A messy table. 

It sounds so silly, but having a messy table at the end of the day and not being able to clean it up before I leave gives me the worst anxiety and definitely stresses me out. 

Even if it’s not completely cleaned off, I like to at least straighten it up before I leave each day. 

I really just HATE coming in in the morning and having stuff allllll over my table and having to start my day like that!!!

Does this make you anxious too!? Or, what really stresses you out as a teacher!?

Let’s make these GIANT paper bag snowflakes!!!!
I have done this the last two years with my class and it’s one of my favorite activities! Definitely works on following directions, listening skills and patience!!!

Materials
-10 paper bags per student (I got the white ones at Walmart for $2 for 50)
-pencil
-scissors
-glue stick
-string to hang

Students needs to make a stencil, then trace their stencil on the remaining bags! They cut out the rest of the bags, glue them together (with the flat side up) and fan them out into a circle! I make sure to tell mine not to make any cuts above the flap line!

They turn out so beautiful and unique! I leave them up through January as a winter decoration!!!

Leaving slides for my sub has been SO helpful this year! I use slides to help guide our day, so it just makes sense to leave the same for a sub! 

We have laptops that our substitutes can use, and when I have a planned absence I upload this to the computer and have it already pulled up and ready to go for them! When I had an unplanned day, I just uploaded my PowerPoint to the substitute program my district uses! 

I like to think it helps keep the routine of our day even though I’m not there!

Do your subs have computers to use!?

I remember a time that I swore I would always do regular morning work. It was a great time to review skills and it was QUIET!!! 

But, with that also came a lot of annoyances. Kids finishing early, some kids not finishing at all. Not having enough time to go over it. Kids stressed about not having enough time.

Now that I do morning tubs, I don’t think I’ll ever change! Never say never, but even with the louder noise, I still like giving my students the chance to just play and explore in the mornings. 

I still have mine structured and I rotate the tub colors each day to my different teams. So they aren’t choice tubs. My kids get to school at different times and I just didn’t want to set up a choice rotation, maybe one day! 

Do you have any questions!?

Here’s how I promote positive behavior!

Individual students can earn Behavior Buddies for showing positive behavior! Each buddy represents a different character word and students get to spend the day with them! They can also nominate each other! 

Teams or groups work together to move their way up to the game board to the finish line! Once they reach the finish line they get to go to the Prize Drop! I don’t have everyone move back to the beginning, they get to stay where they are even when a group reaches the finish!

As a class we work together to earn these rewards! We are working to fill the jar! And we haven’t even talked about a reward, they are just excited to add a piece to the jar!! I got this from @texturesbymaria!

Let me know if you have any questions and stay tuned for part two!!!

Seriously, the BEST and SWEETEST writing activity I’ve ever done!! 

This is one of my most favorite writing pieces because it really gets my students thinking deep about love! As a parent, this is definitely one that would go in their forever box! 

This year my students wrote about their siblings, their families, and added in their interests to write all about what love means, what it looks like, and what it reminds them of!

We also added in the art activity to integrate visual arts! We learned about cool and warm colors and painted our hearts using these colors!

The books Love Is and Love Z are two of my favorites and perfect to help guide the conversations! 

I will add photos of my students holding up hearts with their hands to their writing before I send them home! I’m planning on using Canva to add a fun background!

Hold to read so you don’t end nauseous and anxious too. This reel is literally how my brain feels recently!!!

It’s amazing how I am so used to having my board, for not just teaching but management. It’s my daily schedule, transition music, slides with timers, literally EVERYTHING and the most used item in my classroom. Not having it made me super anxious because I was so out of my routine and I know the kids felt it too. Now there are cords everywhere and it’s definitely not the same but very proud of myself for finding a solution! 

If you’re still reading, thanks for being here and embracing the crazy with me!!!

The days are long but the years are short. 

This quote makes so much more sense the older that I get. They say time flies when you’re having fun. 

I am already half way through my teaching career and in so many ways I feel like I’m still only 25.

But, then I think back on all that I have accomplished over the last 15 years and it’s truly incredible. How much I’ve grown as a teacher, and a human. There have been lots and lots of tears along the way. And so many smiles and laughs. 

I’ve met some of my very best friends and made an impact on someone’s life, not everyone can say that.

While there are so many hard times, I can truly say that I would choose to be a teacher all over again.

The days are long but the years are short.

Mother’s Day gifts in the classroom! I always struggle with what to have my students make for Mother’s Day each year. As a mom, I absolutely love getting a sweet craft or card from my own kids! 

This year we made these pouches and I hope their moms love them! They can be used for anything- pens, makeup, or just a catch all pouch for their purse! 

I got everything on Amazon- the pouches were $20 for 24, and the fabric markers and fabric pens! I just used vinyl and cut out a stencil using a bold font on my @cricut!

Some students followed my rainbow example, some mixed paint colors to make their own, and some painted theirs using their mom’s favorite color! 

I pulled 2-3 students at a time to paint, so it wasn’t overwhelming at all! They didn’t take too long to paint and dried pretty quickly, too!

I hope their moms love them and this ended up being a super simple craft to do this week!

*All my students have a mom to celebrate this weekend! But, I could have easily changed the word to LOVE on the pouch!
Being their mom is my biggest blessing and greatest joy! In so many ways teacher has made me a better mom, and being a mom has made me a better teacher.

Hello Summer!!!!!

The end of the year is such a bittersweet time! And every single year, this transition is always such a strange feeling! 

I go from working like crazy during the entire month of May, to everything just stops! Even after 14 years of doing this, it’s still such a weird feeling!

180 days.

We spent the last 180 days becoming s class family.

We had to take time to get to know each other. Some relationships happened quickly, while others took longer to build. 

There was trust and tears. There were smiles and laughter.

There was learning and growing and mistakes and memories. 

Over the last school year we became a class family and just like that it was time to say goodbye.

We spent 180 days together within these four walls, yet this group of people will never all be together in the same room again.

There’s something about teaching. This is not a job for everyone. Starting on day one and literally building a family day by day, minute by minute. Growing relationships and making memories. And then it’s time to say goodbye and pass them onto a new classroom family. 💖💖💖

There’s just something about a classroom at the beginning of the year! 

It’s clean, and fresh and ready for a new group of students!

It doesn’t last long. As soon as school starts and your students pile in, it becomes more of a home. The piles begin, the floor gets dirty, and there is stuff {literally} everywhere.

Every single year we spend so much time getting our rooms ready. Making sure they are just the way we want them for our new class family! The desks are straight, the tables are clean, the bulletin boards are empty.

There’s just something special about a classroom at the beginning of the year!

These three simple things are actually things I swore I’d never do when I first started teaching! 

💖Having a basket of bandaids for my kids to get whenever they need one! 

💖Eating snack whenever they are working independently!

💖Being able to play and talk instead of traditional morning work.

Of course ALL these things need management and we have to go over the expectations and routines and procedures to make them work! 

Do you do any of these in your classroom! ?

Technically it’s 19 days. But, I’m still not anywhere need ready.

How long do you have left???

This is going to be YEAR FIFTEEN for me!!! Half-way through my career, CRAZY!!!

Favorite way to review all we’ve learned about numbers before fall break….

The NUMBER CIRCUS!!!

The kids LOVE this day! Last year it was one of my kids’ favorite memories at the end of the year, so I had to do it again! 

I honestly don’t do a whole lot of transformation, just some table cloths and a photo backdrop. 

The students rotate between five centers-
-Concession Stand (skip counting or counting coins)
-Lucky Ducks (comparing numbers or value of a digit)
-Clown Toss (adding multiples of 5 and 10)
-Magnificent Numbers (practicing adding and subtracting)
-Popcorn Party (representing 3-digit numbers)

This is NOT currently in my store. I’ve used this the last 3 years with my own kids and that just shows you how awful I am about getting products up on TpT. But I’ll try my best to get it up this weekend if you’re interested!!!!

Here’s how I made these adorable ghosts with my entire class!

Linking all the supplies I used on my @shop.ltk!

Supplies:
-plastic cups
-balloons
-white paper or trash bag for tables
-tea towels (I liked these better than cheese cloth)
-liquid starch 
-small bowls
-felt
-hot glue 

I set up tables with white butcher paper (do not use dark or anything colorful because the ink will get on the ghosts) and put cups with balloons on them. 

I called 2 students at a time to put their tea towel into the liquid starch and then squeeze of the excess. Since the tea towels were pretty big, some of them needed help with this part. Then, they formed the bottom of their ghosts they way they liked it. I just used a post it with their name on it and placed it near the ghost- don’t put it on it while it’s wet because the dye will transfer!

It did take 2 days for these to dry because of how thick the fabric was, so I had to do it in groups! 

Once they were dry, I cut the balloon underneath and students got to cut out pieces of felt for their faces! I did hot glue all their faces on for them!

To poke a hole through, I used a paper clip and then stuck the clear string through and it worked! I was thinking I would need a sewing needle, but it worked better than I thought!

I just use a paper clip and tape at the end of the string to put under my ceiling tiles!

These are ADORABLE! I did them through the week of conferences when we have early release since the days aren’t normal anyway. Then they can hang in our room for at least a week before they take them home on Halloween!

We did read Gustavo before we did this, so a lot of my students made them after the character in the book!

Such a FUN day!!!

Today we did Chatterbox (from my Back from the Break activities) and played Freeze Dance to talk about our breaks!

Then we discussed what makes us SHINE and made these adorable disco balls!!!!

In fifteen years, I did my FIRST countdown and balloon drop and it was completely worth the noise from the noisemakers 😂😂😂🤣

This is my 15th year teaching. I haven’t always loved this job. I haven’t even always liked this job. In fact, I actually quit this job for a year. 

There have been hard days. Hard months. Hard years. 

There’s been so much anxiety and stress from this job. 

But, I still get so much joy from teaching. I realize I’m one of the lucky ones because for so many it’s become miserable. 

I love planning engaging activities and providing joy for my students. And I love being able to share that on this platform.

Thank YOU for being here and sharing in all the real life moments mixed in with the exciting ideas and inspiration for our classrooms!
